            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this mortgage points calculator works</h2>
              <p>This tool compares two scenarios:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Without points</strong> – you pay the standard
                  interest rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>With points</strong> – you pay an upfront fee
                  (discount points) to get a lower rate.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>We then compute:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Loan amount (home price minus down payment)</li>
                <li>Monthly principal &amp; interest in both scenarios</li>
                <li>
                  Total interest over the full term and over your chosen time
                  horizon
                </li>
                <li>
                  Break-even time: when cumulative savings from the lower
                  payment exceed the upfront cost of points
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Formulas used</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Loan amount</strong></p>
                <p>\[ L = P_\text{home} - D \]</p>
                <p>
                  where \(P_\text{home}\) is the home price and \(D\) is the
                  down payment.
                </p>

                <p class="mt-4">
                  <strong
                    >Monthly payment (principal &amp; interest only)</strong
                  >
                </p>
                <p>\[ M = L \cdot \frac{r(1+r)^n}{(1+r)^n - 1} \]</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(L\) = loan amount</li>
                  <li>\(r\) = monthly interest rate = annual rate / 12</li>
                  <li>
                    \(n\) = total number of payments (months) = years × 12
                  </li>
                </ul>

                <p class="mt-4">
                  <strong>Total interest over full term</strong>
                </p>
                <p>\[ I_\text{total} = M \cdot n - L \]</p>

                <p class="mt-4">
                  <strong>Interest over a shorter horizon</strong>
                </p>
                <p>
                  We amortize the loan month by month for your chosen number of
                  years and sum the interest portion of each payment.
                </p>

                <p class="mt-4"><strong>Cost of points</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Points cost} = L \cdot \frac{\text{points}}{100} \]
                </p>

                <p class="mt-4">
                  <strong>Break-even time (approximate)</strong>
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Break-even months} \approx \frac{\text{Points
                  cost}}{M_\text{no points} - M_\text{with points}} \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>What are mortgage points?</h2>
              <p>
                <strong>Mortgage points</strong> (also called
                <strong>discount points</strong>) are an optional upfront fee
                you can pay to your lender in exchange for a lower interest
                rate.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>1 point</strong> usually costs
                  <strong>1% of the loan amount</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Each point typically reduces your rate by about
                  <strong>0.25 percentage points</strong>, but this varies by
                  lender and market.
                </li>
                <li>
                  You can often buy <strong>partial points</strong> (e.g., 0.375
                  points).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                There are also <strong>origination points</strong>, which are a
                lender fee and <em>do not</em> reduce your rate. This calculator
                focuses on <strong>discount points</strong> that buy down the
                rate.
              </p>

              <h3>When paying points can make sense</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  You expect to keep the mortgage for many years (longer than
                  the break-even time).
                </li>
                <li>
                  You have extra cash at closing after covering your down
                  payment and emergency fund.
                </li>
                <li>
                  You want to reduce your monthly payment and total interest
                  over the life of the loan.
                </li>
                <li>You are locking in a long-term fixed-rate mortgage.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>When paying points may not be worth it</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  You plan to <strong>sell or refinance</strong> within a few
                  years.
                </li>
                <li>
                  You are tight on cash for closing costs or emergency savings.
                </li>
                <li>
                  You are close to a key down payment threshold (e.g., 20% to
                  avoid PMI); in that case, more down payment may be better than
                  points.
                </li>
                <li>
                  You are taking an adjustable-rate mortgage and expect to
                  refinance soon.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How to read your results</h2>
              <h3>1. Cost of points</h3>
              <p>
                This is the <strong>upfront cash</strong> you pay at closing.
                For example, on a $320,000 loan:
              </p>
              <p>\[ 1 \text{ point} = 1\% \times 320{,}000 = \$3{,}200 \]</p>

              <h3>2. Monthly savings</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator shows how much lower your monthly principal &amp;
                interest payment is with points. This is your
                <strong>monthly cash-flow benefit</strong>.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Break-even time</h3>
              <p>
                The break-even period tells you how long it takes for the
                monthly savings to repay the upfront cost of points. If you
                expect to keep the loan <strong>longer than this</strong>,
                points are more likely to be a good deal.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Horizon analysis</h3>
              <p>
                Because many people sell or refinance before the end of a
                30-year term, the calculator also compares total interest over
                your chosen <strong>time horizon</strong> (for example, 5–10
                years) and shows your
                <strong>net savings after points cost</strong>.
              </p>

              <h2>Tax considerations (high-level)</h2>
              <p>
                In the U.S., the IRS generally treats
                <strong>discount points</strong> as prepaid mortgage interest.
                Depending on your situation, they may be:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Deductible in the year you pay them (often for a purchase of a
                  primary residence), or
                </li>
                <li>
                  Amortized and deducted over the life of the loan (common for
                  refinances or second homes).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This calculator lets you enter a
                <strong>marginal tax rate</strong> to estimate the after-tax
                cost of points and interest, but it does
                <strong>not</strong> determine whether you are eligible to
                deduct them. Always check the latest IRS guidance and consult a
                tax professional.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips before you decide</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Ask your lender for a <strong>rate sheet</strong> showing
                  several rate/points combinations.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use this calculator to compare each option against the “no
                  points” baseline.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Be realistic about how long you’ll keep the loan—consider job
                  changes, family plans, and likely refinance opportunities.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Don’t drain your <strong>emergency fund</strong> just to buy
                  points.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Compare offers from multiple lenders; the value of points can
                  vary widely.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-6">
